heroIntro: "A liver hydatid cyst is a parasitic infection that often goes unnoticed for years until it is found on a routine scan. Surgery, sometimes combined with medication, offers the most reliable cure. Dr. Reddy performs cystectomy, pericystectomy, and partial liver resection for hydatid disease at Apollo Speciality Hospitals, Nellore."
heroCta:
  label: "Send your scans on WhatsApp"
  message: "Hi Dr. Reddy, I have a liver cyst on my scan and would like a surgical opinion."
sections:
  - type: prose
    title: "What is a liver hydatid cyst?"
    body: "A hydatid cyst is a fluid filled sac in the liver caused by the larval stage of the tapeworm Echinococcus, usually picked up from contact with dogs or sheep. The parasite forms a cyst with a thick wall and clear fluid that can grow slowly over years. Most patients have no symptoms until the cyst becomes large, compresses nearby structures, leaks, or gets infected."
  - type: list
    title: "When is surgery needed?"
    intro: "Treatment depends on the size, location, and stage of the cyst. Surgery is generally recommended when:"
    items:
      - "The cyst is large (typically more than 5 cm)"
      - "The cyst is causing pain or pressure symptoms"
      - "The cyst has ruptured into the bile ducts or peritoneum"
      - "The cyst is infected or contains daughter cysts"
      - "The cyst is in a location with high risk of rupture"
    outro: "Small, calcified, or completely inactive cysts can sometimes be watched safely. Albendazole (an anti parasitic medicine) is usually given before and after surgery to reduce the risk of recurrence."
  - type: list
    title: "Treatment options"
    items:
      - "PAIR (Puncture, Aspiration, Injection, Reaspiration): a needle based procedure done by interventional radiology, suitable for selected uncomplicated cysts"
      - "Open surgery: traditional approach for large, complicated, or deeply placed cysts"
      - "Laparoscopic surgery: minimally invasive option for accessible, uncomplicated cysts"
      - "Cystectomy: removal of the cyst contents and inner layers, leaving the outer wall"
      - "Pericystectomy: complete removal of the cyst including its outer wall, with lower recurrence"
      - "Partial hepatectomy: for very large or deeply embedded cysts where resection is safer"
    outro: "The choice between these depends on cyst size, number, location, and whether bile ducts are involved. Dr. Reddy will discuss the trade offs honestly with you."
  - type: steps
    title: "How the surgery is done"
    steps:
      - "Pre operative albendazole for 1 to 4 weeks to weaken the parasite"
      - "General anaesthesia and laparoscopic or open access"
      - "Isolation of the cyst with packs soaked in a scolicidal agent to prevent spillage"
      - "Careful aspiration of cyst fluid"
      - "Removal of the inner germinal layer and daughter cysts"
      - "Pericystectomy or partial liver resection where appropriate"
      - "Inspection and management of any biliary communication"
      - "Drain placement and closure"
    outro: "Preventing spillage of cyst contents is the central technical priority. Spillage can cause severe allergic reactions and seed new cysts."
  - type: timeline
    title: "Recovery timeline"
    entries:
      - period: "Hospital stay"
        detail: "4 to 7 days for most cases."
      - period: "Drain removal"
        detail: "Usually within the first week, sometimes later if there is bile leak."
      - period: "Diet"
        detail: "Normal diet within a few days."
      - period: "Return to work"
        detail: "2 to 3 weeks for desk work."
      - period: "Full activity"
        detail: "4 to 6 weeks."
      - period: "Post operative albendazole"
        detail: "Usually continued for 1 to 3 months to reduce recurrence."
      - period: "Follow up scans"
        detail: "Ultrasound or CT at intervals over the first 2 to 3 years."
  - type: faqs
    title: "Frequently asked questions"
    faqItems:
      - question: "Can a liver hydatid cyst be treated without surgery?"
        answer: "Small, uncomplicated cysts can sometimes be managed with albendazole alone or with PAIR by interventional radiology. Larger or complicated cysts almost always need surgery for definitive cure."
      - question: "Can the cyst come back after surgery?"
        answer: "Recurrence is uncommon when surgery is done carefully without spillage and combined with albendazole. Long term follow up scans help catch any recurrence early."
      - question: "Is laparoscopic surgery safe for hydatid cysts?"
        answer: "For selected cysts in safe locations, yes. The key is avoiding spillage of cyst contents. Dr. Reddy will decide between laparoscopic and open based on cyst characteristics."
      - question: "Will I need to take medicines lifelong?"
        answer: "No. Albendazole is given for a defined period before and after surgery, usually a few weeks to a few months in total."
